{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500827"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1678"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1678"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.08,0.87,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1678"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"452"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents with a painless swelling on the left side of her neck. This has been present for several years and is slowly increasing is size. It did not bother her until it recently started to discharge foul-smelling material intermittently. There is no history of trauma, or similar complaints in the family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the swelling is non-tender and well-circumscribed (Image). The lesion measures approximately 1.5 cm in diameter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Keloid","Foreign body granuloma","Epidermoid cyst","Neurofibroma","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin is intact over the lesion and a small punctum can be seen. The intermittent discharge supports a diagnosis of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. An epidermoid cyst, is a benign skin lesion originating from the infundibular portion of hair follicles. Typically found on the face, neck, trunk, or genitalia, these cysts manifest as slow-growing, round nodules beneath the skin. A distinctive feature is the central punctum, representing the blocked follicular opening, and gentle pressure can release a cheesy, malodorous substance. While generally painless, complications such as infection may lead to redness and tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeloids a\u003C/strong\u003Ere abnormal, raised overgrowths of scar tissue that extend beyond the original wound. They are more commonly seen in areas of high skin tension, such as the chest and shoulders.Unlike epidermoid cysts, keloids are not subcutaneous nodules with a central punctum\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign body granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E result from a reaction to a retained foreign material in the tissue. Clinically, they may present as nodules with localised inflammation. Unlike epidermoid cysts, foreign body granulomas are associated with a history of trauma or foreign body exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurofibromas\u003C/strong\u003E typically present as soft, rubbery nodules or bumps under the skin. They can vary in size and may be flesh-coloured or slightly pigmented. Neurofibromas can occur anywhere on the body, including along peripheral nerves. Plexiform neurofibromas involve multiple nerve bundles and tend to be larger and deeper than cutaneous neurofibromas. While neurofibromas are generally non-cancerous, they can cause symptoms if they press on nearby nerves or structures. This can result in pain, numbness, or other neurological issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipomas\u003C/strong\u003E are usually soft, mobile, and painless subcutaneous tumours composed of adipose tissue. They are typically not associated with a central punctum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epidermoid cysts can be found almost anywhere on the body and are characterised by a central punctum."],"references":["Dive AM, Khandekar S, Moharil R, et al. Epidermoid cyst of the outer ear: A case report and review of literature. Ind J Otol 2012; 18:34-37"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20484"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20484"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Dum3eL5wWT72dNsBSboNnTAK6cdfS3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Dum3eL5wWT72dNsBSboNnTAK6cdfS3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-12-13T10:01:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T11:48:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1678"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,